# arvo-hash. Design

L2 hash-domain types and algorithm contracts. Ships a domain alias
over the `Bits` storage primitive (now in `arvo-storage`), generic
trait contracts for hash algorithms, and two concrete algorithms:
`XxHash3<const N: Width>` (default) and `Fnv1a<const N: Width>`
(option for known-good fits).

`#![no_std]`, no alloc.

Per round 202604271346: dependencies update. The crate currently
imports through the `arvo` facade (which re-exports `Bits<N, S>`,
`Width`, `Hot`, `UContainerFor`, etc. from the underlying L0 crates).
A future round may switch to direct contract-crate deps
(`arvo-storage`, `arvo-bits-contracts`, `arvo-numeric-contracts`,
`arvo-bitmask`) to tighten the transitive footprint, once
`BitLogic` and `FromConstant` are wired into the algorithm bodies.
The `Hasher<const N: u8>` trait declared here is now `pub const trait`
per D-12, so `hash_const` falls out as a natural feature.

Round 202604280034 dropped the unused direct `arvo-bits` dep that
the previous round's import path made redundant; arvo-hash reaches
the bit-level types through the arvo facade.

## Why this crate exists

Hashes (content hashes, name hashes, pass-key identity) are numeric
algorithms on opaque bit-patterns. The stack needs one home for the
runtime carriers. arvo provides the generic `Bits` container; arvo-
hash provides the domain vocabulary (`ContentHash`), the algo
contracts (`Hasher`, `HasherExt`) consumers parameterise over, and
the canonical first algorithm (`Fnv1a`).

Growth surface (additional concrete algorithms, cryptographic hashes
as a sibling crate, semantic aliases beyond ContentHash) is tracked
in BACKLOG.

## Types

### ContentHash

A type alias for `arvo::Bits<64, Hot>`. Carries the canonical
content-addressed hash identity for downstream consumers
(hilavitkutin-str interner, hilavitkutin-persistence
StringTableEntry, clause resolver pass-key identity, loimu-style
entity content addressing). Consumers that want a named type at
call sites bind `ContentHash` instead of the raw `Bits<64, Hot>`.

```rust
pub type ContentHash = arvo::Bits<64, Hot>;
```

The width widened from 28 to 64 in Pass B.2 of round 202604281000.
64 bits matches `XxHash3`'s natural output and reduces collision
probability to negligible levels for million-entity workloads (the
prior 28-bit identity carried meaningful collision risk past about
16k unique values; 64 bits clears the projected scale by orders of
magnitude).

A direct type alias rather than a newtype: the semantic domain is
fully captured by the bit width; no additional invariants warrant
a distinct type. The `Bits` const-generic widened to `u16` in
Pass F of the same round; only `Hasher` / `Fnv1a` / `XxHash3` lift
to `Width`.

## Algorithm contracts

### Hasher (canonical, streaming)

```rust
use arvo::{Width, Bits, Hot};
use arvo::strategy::{UContainerFor, width_u8};

pub trait Hasher<const N: Width>
where Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u8(N) }>
{
    fn update(&mut self, bytes: &[u8]);
    fn finalize(self) -> Bits<{ width_u8(N) }, Hot>;
}
```

Streaming hash: feed bytes incrementally, finalise to an N-bit
opaque pattern. The const-generic `N: Width` is the meta-newtype
encoding the bit width; the inner `Bits` is sized via `width_u8(N)`
into the L0 storage primitive's `u8` const-generic. Consumers
implementing a hash algorithm implement this trait.

The `&[u8]` parameter is workspace-rule exception #4 (boundary
input from raw bytes; canonical hash input shape).

### HasherExt (oneshot convenience, blanket impl)

```rust
pub trait HasherExt<const N: Width>: Hasher<N> + Sized
where Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u8(N) }>
{
    /// One-shot: update with the complete input, then finalize.
    fn hash(mut self, bytes: &[u8]) -> Bits<{ width_u8(N) }, Hot> {
        self.update(bytes);
        self.finalize()
    }
}
impl<H, const N: Width> HasherExt<N> for H
where
    H: Hasher<N> + Sized,
    Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u8(N) }>,
{}
```

`HasherExt`'s default method provides oneshot ergonomics over any
`Hasher` implementor. The blanket impl means every `Hasher`
automatically exposes a `.hash(bytes)` one-shot form; implementors
do not write their own oneshot path. Mirrors the round-202604201048
Encoder / Decoder + EncoderExt / DecoderExt pattern: streaming is
canonical, oneshot is a derived convenience.

## Default algorithm choice

`XxHash3<const N: Width>` is the default hash family. `Fnv1a<const N: Width>`
remains as an explicit option for known-good fits (small inputs in the
8-16 byte band where FNV-1a stays competitive on bandwidth, or
algorithm-locked test fixtures).

The choice between defaults considered the substrate's primary
consumer workload (16-128 byte entity content addressing, millions
of entities in flight). XxHash3 wins on bandwidth above the 32-byte
input mark; FNV-1a holds at 8-16 bytes. The default crosses the
break-even mark into the consumer's typical band.

Per the `arvo-toolbox-not-policer` workspace rule, both ship; the
consumer picks. `ContentHasher` is the trait; `XxHash3` and `Fnv1a`
are concrete strategies satisfying it.

## Concrete algorithm: XxHash3

```rust
use arvo::{Width, Bits, Hot, width};
use arvo::strategy::{UContainerFor, width_u16, width_le_64};

/// Streaming XxHash3 hasher with N-bit output.
///
/// `XxHash3<{ width(N) }>` produces an N-bit hash via masking from
/// the algorithm's natural 64-bit output. Bound: `N <= 64`.
/// For 128-bit output see the `XxHash3_128` BACKLOG entry.
pub struct XxHash3<const N: Width>
where
    Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u16(N) }>,
    [(); 1 / (width_le_64(N) as usize)]: ;

impl<const N: Width> XxHash3<N>
where
    Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u16(N) }>,
    [(); 1 / (width_le_64(N) as usize)]: ,
{
    pub const fn hash_const(bytes: &[u8]) -> Bits<{ width_u16(N) }, Hot> {
        let raw = xxhash3_64(bytes);
        Bits::<{ width_u16(N) }, Hot>::from_raw_u64(raw)
    }
}

impl<const N: Width> Hasher<N> for XxHash3<N>
where
    Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u16(N) }>,
    [(); 1 / (width_le_64(N) as usize)]: ,
{
    fn update(&mut self, bytes: &[u8]) { /* SRC */ }
    fn finalize(self) -> Bits<{ width_u16(N) }, Hot> { /* SRC */ }
}
```

Same const-eval `N <= 64` guard as `Fnv1a`. Consumer-facing
ergonomics are identical; the algorithmic difference is the body
of `update` / `finalize` and the bandwidth profile.

## Concrete algorithm: Fnv1a

```rust
use arvo::{Width, Bits, Hot, width};
use arvo::strategy::{UContainerFor, width_u8, width_le_64};

/// Streaming FNV-1a-64 hasher with N-bit output.
///
/// `Fnv1a<{ width(N) }>` produces an N-bit hash. Bound: `N <= 64`.
/// For wider widths see the `Fnv1a128` BACKLOG entry.
pub struct Fnv1a<const N: Width>
where
    Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u8(N) }>,
    [(); 1 / (width_le_64(N) as usize)]: ;

impl<const N: Width> Fnv1a<N>
where
    Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u8(N) }>,
    [(); 1 / (width_le_64(N) as usize)]: ,
{
    /// Compile-time hash construction.
    ///
    /// Used by hilavitkutin app-builder for compile-time access-set
    /// hash-membership validation. Const-callable in const-generic
    /// position on the consumer side.
    pub const fn hash_const(bytes: &[u8]) -> Bits<{ width_u8(N) }, Hot> {
        let raw = fnv1a_64(bytes);
        Bits::<{ width_u8(N) }, Hot>::from_raw_u64(raw)
    }
}

impl<const N: Width> Hasher<N> for Fnv1a<N>
where
    Hot: UContainerFor<{ width_u8(N) }>,
    [(); 1 / (width_le_64(N) as usize)]: ,
{
    fn update(&mut self, bytes: &[u8]) { /* SRC */ }
    fn finalize(self) -> Bits<{ width_u8(N) }, Hot> { /* SRC */ }
}
```

The `[(); 1 / (width_le_64(N) as usize)]:` const-eval guard divides
by zero (compile error) when `N > 64`. The `#[diagnostic::on_-
unimplemented]` attribute on `UContainerFor` (defined in arvo)
produces a human-readable strategy-pointing error if the bound is
violated. An out-of-bound use such as `Fnv1a::<{ width(96) }>::hash_-
const(b"x")` triggers the const-eval failure attached to the where-
clause site; the diagnostic message states the `<= 64` constraint
and points at the BACKLOG `Fnv1a128` entry.

`Fnv1a::hash_const` is the entry point for compile-time access-set
hash-membership validation downstream (hilavitkutin app-builder
formalisation, round 202604520000). Streaming `Hasher` impl covers
the runtime path.

